 as Sierra Leone and Australia, Jackson explores variations on this theme. As he describes the ways we address and negotiate the vexed relationships between "I" and "we"—the one and the many—he is also led to consider the place of thought in human life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEthnopsychology. 0aIntersubjectivity. 0aOther minds (Theory of knowledge). 0aPhilosophical anthropology. 0aSelf-perception. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aanthropological books.  aanthropological fieldwork.  aanthropologist experts.  aanthropology and philosophy.  acares and concerns.  acultural studies.  aethnography.  aexistential anthropology.  aglobal anthropology.  ahistory of mankind.  ahuman existence.  ahuman existentialism.  ahuman interactions.  ahuman introspection.  ahuman life.  ahumanist philosophy.  ahumans and conflict.  amoral anthropology.  anature of existence.  aphilosophy of life.  areflecting on life.  areligious studies.  athe palm at the end of the mind.  aworld religions.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027235440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095191440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520951914423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520951914/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY